Data

Here we read in the sleep study data from Project 1 and we retain three variables: cohort and term_gpa as predictors, and TotalSleepTime (renamed sleep) as the response.

df        <- read.csv(url("https://www.stat.cmu.edu/~pfreeman/cmu-sleep.csv"))
df$cohort <- factor(df$cohort)
df %>% select(.,cohort,TotalSleepTime,term_gpa) -> df
names(df)[2] <- "sleep"

Question 1

Let’s first assume that we regress sleep upon cohort. Since the cohorts that appear in the study are a randomly selected subset of all possible cohorts, pursuing learning a random effects model is appropriate (as opposed to a one-way ANOVA model). Learn an appropriate model using lmer() and pass the output to summary(). Display the five intercepts for the five cohorts. (Hint: utilize one of the functions shown in the notes, one specifically used with the Palmer Penguin data.) Last, what is the within-cohort correlation? (This last part involves extracting numbers from the summary() output and “doing math” as opposed to making further function calls.) Is this a weak, medium, or strong correlation? (Use the internet to make that judgement. Note that no two tables mapping correlation coefficients to adjectives seem to match.)

suppressMessages(library(lme4))  # uncomment once the library is installed

# FILL ME IN WITH CODE
model <- lmer(sleep ~ 1 + (1 | cohort), data = df)
summary(model)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']
## Formula: sleep ~ 1 + (1 | cohort)
##    Data: df
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 6747.1
## 
## Scaled residuals: 
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -4.3441 -0.6160  0.0175  0.6454  3.7001 
## 
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Variance Std.Dev.
##  cohort   (Intercept)  205.7   14.34   
##  Residual             2429.7   49.29   
## Number of obs: 634, groups:  cohort, 5
## 
## Fixed effects:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value
## (Intercept)   395.93       6.72   58.91
coef(model)$cohort
##      (Intercept)
## lac1    391.9559
## lac2    381.1778
## nh      385.9503
## uw1     411.6616
## uw2     408.9144
variance_components <- as.data.frame(VarCorr(model))
cohort_variance <- variance_components[1, "vcov"]
residual_variance <- attr(VarCorr(model), "sc")^2

# Calculate within-cohort correlation (ICC)
icc <- cohort_variance / (residual_variance)
icc
## [1] 0.08464209
FILL ME IN WITH TEXT
The correlation within is 0.08464209 which means its weak correlation.

Question 2

Now let’s look at term_gpa. Learn a simple linear regression model that has sleep as the response variable and term_gpa as the predictor variable, and overlay the model on a plot of sleep versus term_gpa. Also, determine the AIC value for the model.

# FILL ME IN WITH CODE

# Fit the simple linear regression model
lm_model <- lm(sleep ~ term_gpa, data = df)

# Display the summary of the model
summary(lm_model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = sleep ~ term_gpa, data = df)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -153.773  -31.975    3.135   31.587  182.478 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  326.627     13.800  23.668  < 2e-16 ***
## term_gpa      20.494      3.959   5.176 3.04e-07 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 49.85 on 632 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.04067,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.03916 
## F-statistic:  26.8 on 1 and 632 DF,  p-value: 3.043e-07
# Create the plot with ggplot
ggplot(df, aes(x = term_gpa, y = sleep)) +
  geom_point() +  # Scatter plot of the data
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", col = "blue") +  # Regression line
  labs(title = "Sleep vs Term GPA", x = "Term GPA", y = "Total Sleep Time (hrs)") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# Calculate AIC for the linear regression model
AIC(lm_model)
## [1] 6759.875

Question 3

Now implement a mixed effects model with term_gpa as the fixed effect and cohort as the random effect, with random intercepts (but same slopes). Output the linear model coefficients for each cohort. (Mentally confirm that indeed, the intercepts are different but the slopes are the same.) And, as you did in Q2, record the AIC value.

No plot is necessary, for now.

# FILL ME IN WITH CODE
# Fit the mixed effects model
mixed_model <- lmer(sleep ~ term_gpa + 1 | cohort, data = df)

# Display the summary of the model

Question 6

Select the best model from among those in Q2-Q5 (i.e., the one with the lowest AIC value). Plot the data again, and overlay the best model…note that this may require you to make five separate calls to geom_abline(). Note that to access the slopes and intercepts, you would use, e.g.,

coefs <- coef(lmer.out)$cohort
coefs[1,1] # first row, first column -- intercept of first cohort
coefs[3,2] # third row, second column -- slope of third cohort
etc.

In the end, your plot may not show five separate lines, which is fine, because the lac1 and lac2, and uw1 and uw2, cohorts had very similar data.

# FILL ME IN WITH CODE
aic_q2 <- AIC(lm_model)  # from Q2
aic_q3 <- AIC(mixed_model)  # from Q3
aic_q4 <- AIC(mixed_model_random_slopes)  # from Q4
aic_q5 <- AIC(mixed_model_random_slopes_intercepts)  # from Q5

# Create a data frame of AIC values for comparison
aic_values <- data.frame(
  Model = c("Q2: Linear Regression", 
            "Q3: Mixed Effects (Random Intercepts)", 
            "Q4: Mixed Effects (Random Slopes)", 
            "Q5: Mixed Effects (Random Slopes and Intercepts)"),
  AIC = c(aic_q2, aic_q3, aic_q4, aic_q5)
)

# Identify the best model with the lowest AIC
best_model <- aic_values[which.min(aic_values$AIC), ]
best_model
##                               Model      AIC
## 3 Q4: Mixed Effects (Random Slopes) 6713.929
# Get the coefficients (intercepts and slopes) from the best model (from Q4)
coefs <- coef(mixed_model_random_slopes)$cohort

# Example: accessing intercept and slope for different cohorts
# coefs[row, column] -> row is cohort, column 1 is intercept, column 2 is slope
coefs[1,1]  # intercept of the first cohort
## [1] 315.4243
coefs[3,2]  # slope of the third cohort
## [1] 19.45821
# Plot the original data (sleep vs term_gpa)
plot <- ggplot(df, aes(x = term_gpa, y = sleep)) +
  geom_point() +  # Scatter plot of the data
  labs(title = "Best Model Overlay: Sleep vs Term GPA",
       x = "Term GPA",
       y = "Total Sleep Time (hrs)") +
  theme_minimal()

# Overlay regression lines for each cohort
# We loop through each cohort and add the corresponding abline (slope and intercept)
for (i in 1:nrow(coefs)) {
  plot <- plot +
    geom_abline(intercept = coefs[i, 1], slope = coefs[i, 2], color = "blue", linetype = "dashed")
}

# Display the final plot
plot
